						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Slab (A-31) in the museum.</hi></p>						

						<p>Achyutarāya—A.D. 1532.</p>						

						<p>This inscription refers itself to the reign of <hi rend="bold">Achyutarāya-Mahārāya</hi> and is dated in <hi rend="bold">Śaka 1455 (current), Nandana, Jyēśhṭha śu. 5, Thursday,</hi> corresponding to <hi rend="bold">A.D. 1532, May 9, Thursday.</hi></p>						

						<p>It states that <hi rend="bold">Chikka Chinnapa—Nayaka,</hi> son of Chinnapa-Nāyaka, the <hi rend="italic">Sēnādhipati</hi> of Achyutarāya renovated the fort of <hi rend="bold">Bādāvi</hi> (modern Bādāmi) and the temple of Banada-Mahāmāyi and other shrines near it, which were all in disrepair.</p>						

						<p>The record is published in <hi rend="italic">Indian Antiquary,</hi> Vol. V, p. 19.</p>						

						</summary>
